tter from Camano Island, October 10, 1994 -- tAppendix 1. Canyon Cinema Employees, 1969 to the Present -- tAppendix 2. Canyon Cinema’s Gross Rentals and Sales, from 1966 until 2006–2007 -- tAcknowledgments of Permissions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing alive a remarkable moment in American cultural history, Scott MacDonald tells the colorful story of how a small, backyard organization in the San Francisco Bay Area emerged in the 1960s and evolved to become a major force in the development of independent cinema. Drawing from extensive conversations with men and women crucial to Canyon Cinema, from its newsletter Canyon Cinemanews, and from other key sources, MacDonald offers a lively chronicle of the life and times of this influential, idiosyncratic film exhibition and distribution collective. His book features many primary documents that are as engaging and relevant now as they were when originally published, including essays, poetry, experimental writing, and drawings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndependent filmszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american film culture.  a20th century american film history.  aamerican cultural history.  aarmy surplus screen.  aavant garde films.  abruce baillie.  acanyon california.  acanyon cinema.  acanyon cinemanews.  acinema.  aexhibition outlet.  aexperimental films.  aexperimental writings.  afilm distribution collective.  afilmmakers cooperative.  afilms.  aindependent film cinema.  aindependent films.  aindependent movie pictures.  amovies.  asan francisco bay area.  asan francisco cinematheque.1 aBaillie, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a